stories: Patients suffering from musculoskeletal disorders and cognitive impairments experience challenges in movement, resulting in adverse psychological consequences. Clinical gait analysis, an essential method for identifying these conditions early and administering appropriate treatment, has typically depended on costly optical motion capture systems. However, advancements in computer vision and deep learning technology have paved the way for more affordable and accessible alternatives. This study presents a new spatio-temporal transformer network for calculating crucial gait measurements from RGB videos taken by a standard single-view camera. Tests on a publicly available dataset of cerebral palsy patients reveal that this framework outperforms existing techniques and yields substantial enhancements in estimating general gait characteristics (such as walking speed, gait deviation index - GDI, and maximum knee flexion angle), all while reducing the number of required parameters and eliminating the need for manual feature extraction.

Individuals dealing with musculoskeletal issues and cognitive impairments face difficulties in movement, leading to unfavorable psychological outcomes. Clinical gait analysis, a vital tool for identifying these conditions early and delivering suitable treatment, has historically relied on expensive optical motion capture systems. Nevertheless, innovations in computer vision and deep learning technology have opened up more affordable and accessible alternatives. In this research, we introduce a novel spatio-temporal transformer network for determining vital gait metrics from RGB videos recorded by a conventional single-view camera. Trials on a publicly accessible dataset of cerebral palsy patients demonstrate that this approach surpasses existing methods and provides significant improvements in evaluating general gait traits (including walking speed, gait deviation index - GDI, and maximum knee flexion angle), all while decreasing the necessity of parameters and eliminating the requirement for manual feature extraction.

People with musculoskeletal problems and cognitive impairments encounter challenges in mobility, which can result in unwanted psychological consequences. Early identification and appropriate treatment of these conditions have traditionally depended on costly optical motion capture systems for clinical gait analysis. However, advancements in computer vision and deep learning technology have brought about more affordable and accessible options. In this study, we present a new spatio-temporal transformer network designed to extract essential gait metrics from RGB videos captured by a regular single-view camera. Tests on a publicly available dataset of cerebral palsy patients have shown that this method outperforms existing techniques and delivers substantial enhancements in assessing overall gait characteristics (such as walking speed, gait deviation index - GDI, and maximum knee flexion angle), with a reduction in the need for parameters and the elimination of manual feature extraction.

Individuals dealing with musculoskeletal problems and declining cognitive functions might encounter unwanted psychological repercussions. Traditionally, diagnosing and addressing these complications have relied on costly motion capture equipment, primarily used in hospitals for extensive gait evaluations. However, recent advancements in computer vision and deep learning offer more affordable and accessible alternatives. The following study introduces a novel spatio-temporal transformer network, which can extract essential gait data from standard RGB videos using a solitary camera perspective. Preliminary studies on a publicly available cerebral palsy database suggest superior performance compared to existing techniques, broadening the gait analysis field and bringing attention to aspects like walking pace, Gait Deviation Index (GDI), and maximum knee flexion angle. Furthermore, it obviates the need for time-consuming manual feature extraction.
